{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a1b2c3d4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Data Collection — Portugal Housing Rent Statistics\n",
    "\n",
    "This notebook documents where the rent data comes from and how I turned the raw\n",
    "INE download into the clean `portugal_rents.csv` used by the interactive map.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Source:** INE (Statistics Portugal) — *Estatísticas das Rendas de Habitação*,\n",
    "1.º Trimestre 2026.  \n",
    "The data is published as a quarterly press release on the INE website at\n",
    "https://www.ine.pt (search for "Rendas de Habitação"). The press release comes\n",
    "with an Excel file that has municipality-level figures alongside the NUTS\n",
    "regional aggregates.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why INE and not something else?**  \n",
    "INE is the official national statistics agency, so this is about as authoritative\n",
    "as it gets. The data covers *new* lease agreements only — it doesn't tell you\n",
    "what existing tenants pay, just what the market price is right now if you go\n",
    "looking for a flat.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "**To reproduce this notebook you need:**\n",
    "1. The raw Excel file from INE saved as `ine_rendas_t1_2026.xlsx` in the same\n",
    "   folder. It is listed in `.gitignore` because it's large and not mine to\n",
    "   redistribute — download it directly from the INE press release page.\n",
    "2. `pip install pandas openpyxl`"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "b2c3d4e5",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import pandas as pd"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c3d4e5f6",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Step 1 — Load the raw file\n",
    "\n",
    "The INE Excel has several sheets. The one I need is the table that shows\n",
    "median rent per m² by municipality. INE only publishes individual municipality\n",
    "figures for places with **at least 100 new lease agreements** in the quarter —\n",
    "smaller municipalities get grouped into their NUTS III sub-region.\n",
    "\n",
    "I had to open the file in Excel first to figure out the sheet name and where\n",
    "the data actually starts, because INE files tend to have several rows of\n",
    "title/metadata before the table."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "d4e5f6g7",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Load the sheet with the municipality-level breakdown.\n",
    "# header=None because the real headers are buried a few rows down.\n",
    "raw = pd.read_excel(\"ine_rendas_t1_2026.xlsx\", sheet_name=\"Quadro 4\", header=None)\n",
    "print(raw.shape)\n",
    "raw.head(15)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e5f6g7h8",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Step 2 — Find where the data rows start\n",
    "\n",
    "INE files typically have a big merged-cell title, then a sub-title, then the\n",
    "column headers (which are also often merged), and only then the actual rows.\n",
    "I need to figure out which row index marks the start of the real data.\n",
    "\n",
    "I do this by scanning for the first row where the first column looks like an\n",
    "actual place name rather than a label/number."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "f6g7h8i9",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Print rows 5-20 to find where the header row is\n",
    "raw.iloc[5:20]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "g7h8i9j0",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Based on inspection: data starts at row 9, the useful columns are 0 (name) and\n",
    "# the column with Q1 2026 median rent (adjust index after looking at the file).\n",
    "# I rename them right away so the rest of the code is readable.\n",
    "\n",
    "DATA_START = 9     # first actual data row (0-indexed)\n",
    "NAME_COL   = 0     # column with the area name\n",
    "RENT_COL   = 5     # column with median rent €/m² for Q1 2026\n",
    "\n",
    "df = raw.iloc[DATA_START:, [NAME_COL, RENT_COL]].copy()\n",
    "df.columns = [\"zone\", \"price_m2\"]\n",
    "df = df.dropna(subset=[\"zone\", \"price_m2\"]).reset_index(drop=True)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Make sure the rent column is numeric (INE sometimes stores it as a string)\n",
    "df[\"price_m2\"] = pd.to_numeric(df[\"price_m2\"], errors=\"coerce\")\n",
    "df = df.dropna(subset=[\"price_m2\"])\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"{len(df)} rows loaded\")\n",
    "df.head(10)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "h8i9j0k1",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Step 3 — Add hierarchy labels\n",
    "\n",
    "The INE file has a nested structure: national total → NUTS I → NUTS II → NUTS III →\n",
    "municipalities. I need to tag each row with its level so the map can use the\n",
    "right fallback value when a municipality doesn't have its own figure.\n",
    "\n",
    "I do this by cross-referencing with a lookup I built by hand from the\n",
    "[NUTS 2013 classification](https://www.ine.pt/xportal/xmain?xpid=INE&xpgid=ine_main)\n",
    "— it's a small enough list that I could just type it out."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "i9j0k1l2",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# These are the names as they appear in the INE file.\n",
    "NUTS2 = {\n",
    "    \"Norte\", \"Centro\", \"Área Metropolitana de Lisboa\",\n",
    "    \"Alentejo\", \"Algarve\", \"Região Autónoma dos Açores\",\n",
    "    \"Região Autónoma da Madeira\",\n",
    "    # INE also groups some regions differently:\n",
    "    \"Oeste e Vale do Tejo\",\n",
    "}\n",
    "\n",
    "NUTS3 = {\n",
    "    \"Alto Minho\", \"Cávado\", \"Ave\", \"Área Metropolitana do Porto\",\n",
    "    \"Alto Tâmega e Barroso\", \"Tâmega e Sousa\", \"Douro\",\n",
    "    \"Terras de Trás-os-Montes\", \"Região de Aveiro\", \"Região de Coimbra\",\n",
    "    \"Região de Leiria\", \"Viseu Dão Lafões\", \"Beira Baixa\",\n",
    "    \"Beiras e Serra da Estrela\", \"Oeste\", \"Médio Tejo\",\n",
    "    \"Lezíria do Tejo\", \"Grande Lisboa\", \"Península de Setúbal\",\n",
    "    \"Alentejo Litoral\", \"Baixo Alentejo\", \"Alto Alentejo\",\n",
    "    \"Alentejo Central\", \"Algarve\",\n",
    "    # non-mainland (excluded from the map)\n",
    "    \"Oeste e Vale do Tejo\",\n",
    "}\n",
    "\n",
    "def assign_level(name):\n",
    "    if name in (\"Portugal\", \"Continente\"):\n",
    "        return \"country\"\n",
    "    if name in NUTS2:\n",
    "        return \"nuts2\"\n",
    "    if name in NUTS3:\n",
    "        return \"nuts3\"\n",
    "    return \"municipality\"\n",
    "\n",
    "df[\"level\"] = df[\"zone\"].apply(assign_level)\n",
    "df[\"level\"].value_counts()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "j0k1l2m3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Step 4 — Calculate the 1-bedroom estimate\n",
    "\n",
    "The INE data gives price per m², not an actual rent. To make the numbers more\n",
    "relatable, I estimate the cost of a one-bedroom flat by multiplying by 45 m²\n",
    "(a rough average size for a T1 in Portugal). This is a simplification — a T1\n",
    "in Lisbon is probably smaller, and one in the Alentejo probably bigger — but\n",
    "it gives a comparable figure across regions.\n",
    "\n",
    "This is the same assumption used in the article headline."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "k1l2m3n4",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "df[\"rent_t1_45m2\"] = (df[\"price_m2\"] * 45).round(2)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Keep only mainland Portugal (drop Azores and Madeira — the geojson doesn't cover them)\n",
    "exclude = {\"Região Autónoma dos Açores\", \"Região Autónoma da Madeira\"}\n",
    "df = df[~df[\"zone\"].isin(exclude)].reset_index(drop=True)\n",
    "\n",
    "df = df[[\"zone\", \"level\", \"price_m2\", \"rent_t1_45m2\"]]\n",
    "print(df.shape)\n",
    "df.head(10)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "l2m3n4o5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Step 5 — Save\n",
    "\n",
    "This CSV is what `index.html` reads to colour the map. I round to 2 decimal\n",
    "places to keep the file small."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "m3n4o5p6",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "df.to_csv(\"portugal_rents.csv\", index=False)\n",
    "print(\"Saved portugal_rents.csv\")\n",
    "df.tail()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "n4o5p6q7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "**Limitations of this approach**\n",
    "\n",
    "- The INE only gives a figure for a municipality if it had ≥ 100 new leases\n",
    "  in the quarter. Smaller/rural places fall back to their NUTS III region, which\n",
    "  can mask big local differences.\n",
    "- These are *new* lease medians — they represent what you pay if you sign a\n",
    "  contract today, not what existing tenants pay (that figure is usually lower).\n",
    "- The geometry file covers 278 mainland municipalities; the data only has explicit\n",
    "  figures for about 23 of them. The map still looks full because the NUTS fallback\n",
    "  fills the gaps, but it's worth knowing most colours are estimates.\n",
    "\n",
    "If I had more time, it would be interesting to look at the time series data\n",
    "(INE has quarterly data going back several years) to show *how much* rents\n",
    "have changed, not just where they stand now."
   ]
  }
 ],
